    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-03-29T22:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-03-29T22:19:00-05:00" n="14"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d14">
                <head>14. Transcript of a Telephone Conversation Between President <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> and the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
                    Staff (<persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d14fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials,
                        White House Tapes, Recording of a Conversation between <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1"
                            >Moorer</persName>, White House Telephone, Conversation No. 44–92. No
                        classification marking. The editors transcribed this tape recording
                        specifically for this volume.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1973-03-29T22:19:00-05:00" to="1973-03-29T22:23:00-05:00">March
                            29, 1973, 10:19–10:23 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: How’d you like what I said about
                    national defense, Admiral?<note n="2" xml:id="d14fn2">On March 29, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> addressed the nation regarding
                        Vietnam and domestic problems, devoting a portion of his remarks to
                        defending the military and the defense budget. For the full text of
                            <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>’s address, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Public Papers: <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1"
                                >Nixon</persName>, 1973</hi>, pp. 234–238.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: That was fine, sir. We’ve been
                    up struggling on—</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: Look, fight like hell for the
                    budget. We cannot cut the budget.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Yes, sir. We spent five days
                    already on it, and we are working hard on the <persName corresp="#p_SWS_1"
                        >Symington</persName> committee now.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: Put it to them on the basis that
                    if they cut this budget they will destroy the chances for <gloss
                        target="#t_MBFR_1">MBFR</gloss> and for the deal with the Soviet. The
                        Soviet—<persName corresp="#p_BL_1">Brezhnev</persName>, I know, I’m going to
                    meet the son-of-a-bitch this summer.<note n="3" xml:id="d14fn3">See <ref
                            target="#d7fn2">footnote 2, Document 7</ref>.</note> And he’ll be there.
                    And if we’ve already cut, he won’t give me a damn thing.</p>
                <pb facs="0086" n="44" xml:id="pg_44"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: You’re right, sir. That’s
                    exactly what—</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: I think I got that point across.
                    You can’t—that the rule of diplomacy, one unbreakable rule—is that you can’t get
                    anything unless you’ve got something to give.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Exactly. Yes, sir. Well we’re
                    doing our best. We’re finished with the Senate now. We’ve got the House
                    Appropriations Committee and then the Armed Services Committee.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: Just make the point—</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Yes, sir.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>:—that those who cut the budget
                    will destroy the chances for reduction of armaments, or limitation of armaments,
                    and for peace.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Right, sir.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: Okay.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Well we’ll lay it on them as
                    hard as we can.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>: All right. Thank you,
                    Admiral.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>: Again, thank you, sir.</p>
            </div>
